New sources identified this session (not yet integrated into V2):
Cooley & Brown-Iannuzzi et al., "White Americans' feelings of being 'last place' are associated with anti-DEI attitudes, Trump support, and Trump vote during the 2024 U.S. presidential election," Advances in Psychology (2026) â€” peer-reviewed, longitudinal, census-weighted. Key finding: it's perceived racial status position, not objective income/education, that predicts Trump support. 15% of sample fit "last place (tied with Black Americans)" profile. Directly supports Section V's horizontal friction argument with fresh empirical data.
Jared Wesley commissioned paper for Public Order Emergency Commission â€” traces Alberta separatism and Freedom Convoy to "status loss, political tribalism, and the death of deference to traditional forms of authority." Explicitly names status loss. Also references separate paper: Snagovsky, Maroto & Wesley, "White Identity and Western Alienation in Alberta" (2022).
Tamara Krawchenko, The Conversation (Feb 15, 2026) â€” "As Alberta separatists court the U.S., prosperity is fuelling a sovereigntist turn." Key line: Alberta's anger "stems from believing it matters a great deal and is nonetheless disrespected." Under-recognized importance, not marginality. Identifies three-way collision: cultivated grievance politics + self-inflicted fiscal vulnerability + energy transition threatening regional identity.
Maclean's, "Alberta's New Separatists" (2025) â€” concrete data on relative income decline: Alberta median family incomes were 30% above national average before 2014 oil crash, now only 15% above. Still richer, but the gap narrowed. Perceived falling = political fuel.
Common Ground / Samuel Goertz focus group research (2025) â€” 21 focus groups, 200 Albertans, 4,068km across province. "Joe" (composite typical Albertan) feels overlooked and disrespected specifically by Ontario, Quebec, Vancouver. Not poorer â€” disrespected. Separatism used as leverage ("Quebec Playbook"), not genuine desire to leave.
RESEARCH NOTES: STATUS LOSS IN ALBERTA
The core paradox: Alberta is objectively Canada's wealthiest province by most measures â€” highest median incomes, lowest unemployment, fastest growth since 1950. Yet it hosts Canada's most intense separatist movement. This combination is diagnostic: it points to status grievance, not economic grievance.
The mechanism (parallel to PsyPost study):
US finding: White Americans who perceive themselves tied with Black Americans at the bottom of the racial hierarchy (not the actually poorest) are most likely to support Trump. Perceived relative decline, not absolute poverty.
Alberta parallel: Province still richer than rest of Canada, but gap has narrowed since 2014. Experienced as falling. The grievance is under-recognized importance â€” "we carry the country and are treated as subordinates."
The equalization mechanism: Alberta sends money to Ottawa for redistribution to "have-not" provinces. Experienced not as national solidarity but as being drained to subsidise others. The key status claim: western interests are treated as "regional" while central Canadian interests are treated as "national." Alberta's concerns don't count as Canada's concerns.
The identity dimension: Oil is not just an industry â€” it's the basis of Alberta's self-image and regional identity. Federal decarbonization policy is heard as: "your identity is a problem to be managed." Status threat becomes existential.
The portable mechanism: The PsyPost study shows status-threat â†’ horizontal anger operating along racial lines in the US. Alberta shows the same mechanism operating along regional/identity lines in Canada. Different vocabulary (not race but region), same underlying psychology. This suggests the horizontal/vertical friction dynamic is not culturally specific â€” it's a general human response to perceived status decline that attaches to whatever hierarchy is locally salient.
Essay implication: Alberta could serve as the Canadian case study that demonstrates the pattern's portability â€” and Max's personal position inside it gives it journalistic force that pure American data cannot.
PERSONAL NARRATIVE FRAME
Max began this project after unproductively arguing with Alberta separatists online using a burner Facebook account. The project became a way to understand why societies fracture â€” and ended up changing how he sees those neighbours. The essay's intellectual argument (horizontal vs. vertical friction) mirrors his personal journey: from horizontal friction (trolling separatists) to vertical analysis (examining power structures).
This transformation is the spine of the Substack framing. The personal story and the intellectual argument are the same story told at different scales.
The crucial context: Max is not writing about separatism and social contract collapse as history. He is living inside an active separatist movement in real time. Alberta in 2025â€“2026 is a live case study of everything the essay describes â€” a province with genuine economic grievances (oil revenues, equalization payments, federal overreach) whose anger has been directed horizontally (at Ottawa, at central Canada, at Trudeau, at "elites") rather than vertically at the structural forces actually responsible. The essay's thesis is not abstract from where Max sits. It is the news.
A NOTE ON AI COLLABORATION HONESTY
A pivotal moment in this project: Max identified a quote in the essay as "too good to be original." It was from Mark Carney. This led to tracing the horizontal/vertical friction concept back to Piven and Cloward â€” acknowledging synthesis rather than original theory. When Max tested Claude's knowledge against another AI's claims about Poor People's Movements, Claude expressed appropriate uncertainty while the other AI provided confident but inaccurate details. Max uploaded the actual text â€” Claude's caution was vindicated.
These moments are not embarrassments. They are the methodology. They get documented in the director's notes.
